snippet.textDisplay: As someone who has BPD this show is well... one the best representation of mental health when it comes to untreated/undertreated BPD. I remember starting to watch the first season and looking at my partner after about episode 11 and saying "I am pretty sure Rebecca has BPD" and he thought about it and was like "yeah she totally could. I wonder if that is intentional or not" then later you do in fact get that payoff where it is diagnosed with BPD and I felt so fucking seen. There isn't a lot of media that betrays mental health, especially personality disorders in a more healthy way. It is constructive, has consequences for actions, shows diagnose and the first ripple effects of the diagnoses, and shows the start of a healthy journey living with not ignoring your mental health diagnoses. This sort of visibility is important - especially for personality disorders since almost always those end up being negative stereotype based caricatures of people who have them.
snippet.textOriginal: As someone who has BPD this show is well... one the best representation of mental health when it comes to untreated/undertreated BPD. I wonder if that is intentional or not" then later you do in fact get that payoff where it is diagnosed with BPD and I felt so fucking seen. There isn't a lot of media that betrays mental health, especially personality disorders in a more healthy way.
